    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Radio Frequency Propagation Investigations for Wireless Sensor</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Balachander.D</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Radio Frequency<br />Wireless Sensor</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nov-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0132</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Recent advancements in cellular and wireless communications have
resulted in the ability to integrate sensors, wireless communications and digital
electronics into a single integrated circuit package. This capability enables networks
that comprise very low cost sensors and that are able to communicate with each other.
Measuring, monitoring and controlling almost any process is becoming feasible with
the current generation wireless sensors. Further, equipped with the strides in indoor
localization technologies, the focus is now on applications that will change our day to
day life. Thus, Wireless Sensor Networks (WSNs) are emerging as a significant
technology and have the potential to revolutionize the process of harnessing of data
from the physical world, enabling applications that previously were not practical and
are drawing attention and interest for its applications in different fields.
Precise estimation of propagation losses offers proper selection of
transmitter locations and hence the radio link characteristic should be properly
understood especially for networks such as randomly deployable, low powered WSNs.
Therefore, there is a need for evaluating the actual radio link behavior and the effect of
local geometry on the radio channel of the WSNs for a wide variety of applications in
indoor and outdoor environments. Thus, short-range, near-floor experimental
propagation measurements were taken in indoor corridors of a high raised building and
outdoor environments such as tropical dry evergreen forest / plantations, agriculture
fields / gardens utilizing RF equipment and compared with Matlab simulations of
various propagation prediction models.
From extensive propagation measurements, it is evident that the building
materials and furnishings can affect indoor propagation, and so the use of low
absorption material such as plywood on floor and walls of indoor environments will
provide better RSS. Indoor localization technologies are making progress with the aid
of mapping, object tracking, surveillance and detection where the available RSS plays
vital role in coverage and signal quality issues. Apart from propagation measurements,
linear regression based modeling has been done and the proposed model has been
observed to be suitable for path loss prediction in indoor corridor environments.
In outdoor environments, where there is vegetation in the radio link path,
COST 235 model gives consistently low RMSEs and is suitable for WSN planning and
deployment in tropical dry evergreen forest / plantations, agriculture fields / garden
environments, especially in tropical climate regions.
Based on extensive propagation measurements, the radio frequency, 915
MHz gives lower mean path loss values in both indoor and outdoor environments. The
research work on short-range, near-floor RSS based RF propagation demonstrated the
variation between several measurement approaches, and highlights the differences
between commonly used modeling techniques. And, the efforts made towards
understanding propagation losses in indoor and outdoor environments will support
WSN planners and system designers, indoor location based wireless technologies and
precision agriculture based wireless technologies, which are expected to proliferate
across a very wide variety of consumer devices in the near future.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13838">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13838</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
